\begin_layout Standard
We plan to assess the impact of the intervention on household-level agricultural
 outcomes, with a focus on the adoption of recommended inputs and practices,
 crop yields, profitability, and returns on investment in fertilizer and
 subsidies.
 Rather than limiting the analysis to plot-level data from the experimental
 site, we will capture broader effects on household decision-making processes,
 including crop mix adjustments, and the allocation of crops across different
 plots.
 The primary set of outcomes focuses on direct impacts related to fertilizer
 use and associated agricultural practices.
 Key measures will include whether farmers used any fertilizer, the extent
 to which they adopted the recommended type, and the rate of application
 (amount of fertilizer applied per hectare).
 We will also evaluate the impact on proper fertilizer application practices,
 defined as applying the fertilizer at the right place, right time, and
 right rate.
 These will be measured as a deviation from recommended practices, e.g., the
 gap between recommended application rates and actual application rates
 will be used to arrive at an “application error” outcome.
 In addition, we will assess outcomes related to yield and value of production,
 profitability, and returns on fertilizer investment.
 Additionally, we will evaluate the impact of the intervention on farmers’
 subjective assessments of the effectiveness of the fertilizer type they
 used on yield.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A secondary set of outcomes explores complementary practices and broader
 changes in agricultural behavior that may arise as a result of the intervention.
 This includes potential shifts in the crop mix farmers are planting.
 The intervention may also affect labor allocation, prompting increased
 use of both family and hired labor as farming intensity changes.
 Furthermore, changes in the use and costs of complementary inputs, such
 as improved seed varieties or agricultural chemicals (e.g., pesticides, fungicide
s), will be assessed.
 The study will also explore shifts in soil nutrient management practices,
 including the use of organic fertilizer (e.g., manure), or techniques like
 minimum tillage, mulching, crop rotation, and residue incorporation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the implementation and uptake of the intervention, we will
 collect data on several intermediary outcomes.
 This will include whether soil testing was conducted, if tailored fertilizer
 advice was received, and whether vouchers were distributed and redeemed
 at local outlets, such as Farmers World.
 We will gather details about the farmers' experiences at agro-input dealers,
 including whether the recommended fertilizer blend was available, any issues
 encountered with the subsidy amount, and the process for paying for fertilizer
 beyond what was covered by the voucher.
 
\end_layout

